<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910916-0030</DOCNO><DOCID>910916-0030.</DOCID><HL>   Ten Foreign Affiliates   Express Their Interest   In a Japanese Project   ----   Special to the Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>09/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   G.SIE HIT IBM J.FAN J.OLO J.SMD J.TOS</CO><MS>INDUSTRIAL (IDU)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)ELECTRICAL COMPONENTS AND EQUIPMENT (ELQ)DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)INDUSTRIAL TECHNOLOGY andamp; PRODUCTION, QUALITY CONTROL (ITC)MEDICAL SUPPLIES, EYEGLASS MANUFACTURERS (MDS)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)GERMANY (GE)JAPAN (JA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   TOKYO -- Ten foreign-affiliated companies, includingSiemens AG and IBM Japan Ltd., informed a Japaneseextra-governmental research and development organization oftheir interest in its &quot;micro machine&quot; project, an official atthe organization said.   &quot;Micro machine&quot; includes technologies that allowmanufacturing of extremely tiny elements that could makepossible the making of machines small enough to go throughthe eye of a needle.</LP><TEXT>   The official at the New Energy and Industrial TechnologyDevelopment Organization, or NEDO, declined to identify theeight other foreign affiliates.   In a step toward reducing technology frictions, he saidhis organization expects to invite companies, includingforeign concerns, to join in the next-generation mechanismproject from the end of this month.   Although nothing has been decided yet, the organizationhopes to narrow down participants to between 10 and 20companies by the beginning of next year. Nearly 100 companieshave informed the organization of their interest in theproject.   Japanese companies that have expressed interest includeHitachi Ltd., Toshiba Corp., Fanuc Ltd., Yaskawa ElectricMfg. Co., Shimadzu Corp. and Olympus Optical Co.   The project, which was consigned to the organization bythe Ministry of International Trade and Industry, will have alife of 10 years. It started from the current fiscal year.</TEXT></DOC>